This again shows an advantage of weekly paclitaxel and every-3-week docetaxel compared to every-3-week paclitaxel.

Both studies do not clearly state superiority of AC-T over AC-D or vice versa when comparing same schedule. However, from the first study, it is noted that, "Weekly paclitaxel improved DFS and OS (HR, 0.69; P = .010 and HR, 0.69; P = .019, respectively) in triple-negative breast cancer".

The evidence describes a trial comparing "rapidly cycled tandem high-dose chemotherapy plus peripheral-blood stem-cell support" to "dose-dense conventional chemotherapy." The "dose-dense conventional chemotherapy" regimen consisted of four cycles of epirubicin and cyclophosphamide followed by three cycles of accelerated cyclophosphamide, methotrexate, and fluorouracil. This corresponds to ddEC-ddCMF. The "rapidly cycled tandem high-dose chemotherapy" involved two cycles of accelerated (2-week intervals) conventionally dosed epirubicin and cyclophosphamide followed by two cycles of high-dose chemotherapy (epirubicin, cyclophosphamide, and thiotepa supported by peripheral-blood progenitors). This corresponds to EC, then ECT, then auto HSCT.

The results showed that 4-year event-free survival was 60% in the high-dose chemotherapy group (EC, then ECT, then auto HSCT) and 44% in the control group (ddEC-ddCMF) (p=0.00069). The corresponding overall survival was 75% versus 70% (p=0.02). Since the high-dose chemotherapy group (EC, then ECT, then auto HSCT) had statistically significant superior event-free survival and overall survival, the ddEC-ddCMF is considered inferior.
